\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Les Poissons, les Poissons, how I love les Poissons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, we considered the 1d Poisson equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u(x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

 for the vector space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,L]$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dirichlet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=u(L)=0$
\end_inset

, and solved it in terms of the eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (giving a Fourier sine series).
 Here, we will consider a couple of small variations on this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How do the eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}$
\end_inset

 change if we change the boundary conditions to 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(L)=0$
\end_inset

 (note prime = 1st derivative)? Check by explicit integration that different-eig
envalue eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}$
\end_inset

 are still orthogonal in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{L}u_{n}(x)u_{m}(x)dx=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

