\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: Nondimensionalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 18.303, we will mostly solve PDEs in convenient arbitrary units where
 we don't have any pesky dimensionful constants flapping around the equations
 and annoying us.
 This represents no loss of generality because, even if someone hands you
 a a PDE in SI units, you can always rescale things to get back into dimensionle
ss form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In quantum mechanics, they study the Schrodinger equation: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}+V(\vec{x})\right]\psi=i\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}\]

\end_inset

in the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\vec{x},t)$
\end_inset

.
 Show how, by a change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\vec{x}}=\vec{x}/X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{t}=t/T$
\end_inset

, for appropriately chosen scale factors 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula ${}=?$
\end_inset

), you can transform this into a simplified equation: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[-\tilde{\nabla}^{2}+V(X\tilde{\vec{x}})\right]\tilde{\psi}=i\frac{\partial\tilde{\psi}}{\partial\tilde{t}}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\psi}(\tilde{\vec{x}},\tilde{t})=\psi(X\tilde{\vec{x}},T\tilde{t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the Laplacian in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\vec{x}}$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
 (Hint: first figure out how 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}^{2}\tilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\tilde{\psi}/\partial\tilde{t}$
\end_inset

 relate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\psi/\partial t$
\end_inset

, respectively.)
